ports clubs, which began to thrive beyond the confines of school systems. ‹i›Futbolera‹/i› examines how women challenged both their exclusion from national pastimes and their lack of access to leisure, bodily integrity, and public space. This vibrant history also examines women&#x2019;s sports through comparative case studies of Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Costa Rica, Mexico, and others. Special attention is given to women&#x2019;s sports during military dictatorships of the 1970s and 1980s as well as the feminist and democratic movements that followed. The book culminates by exploring recent shifts in mindset toward women&#x2019;s football and dynamic social movements of players across Latin America.‹/p›  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aSoccer for womenzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aSoccerxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aSoccerzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aSports for womenxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aSports for womenzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aWomen athleteszLatin AmericaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aNadel, Joshua, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074529040uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31042740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477318584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477318584/original  a978-3-11-074529-0  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK